snippet.textDisplay: The ref didn’t rob Wilder in fight 1, the judges ripped Fury off by calling it a draw. Fury won 10 of 12 rounds , at the least 9 rounds and even with 2 rounds being 10-8,  he STILL won the fight on points. The 10 count is one of the most misunderstood rules in sport. It is NOT a 10 second count per se, with a stopwatch. It is a 10 count and judges at ringside start the count when the fighter is downed. The ref usually directs the standing fighter to a neutral corner then picks up the the count by looking over at the time keeper and picks up the count from that point. Yes, it’s designed to be about 10 seconds but it is not necessarily exactly 10 seconds. It is a10 count synchronized between the judge or timekeeper at ringside and the ref. Hence, Tyson Fury is rightfully 31-0 and Deontay Wilder is 41-2.
